          "body": "Psalm 71 is organized in three interlocking spirals. Cycle 1 (71:1-8) opens with petition (rescue me, 71:1-4), grounds it in testimony (You have sustained me from birth, 71:5-6), and closes with a vow of continuous praise (my mouth is filled with Your praise all day long, 71:8). Cycle 2 (71:9-16) opens with the most urgent petition (do not cast me off in old age, 71:9), names the threat explicitly (71:10-11), then pivots sharply at 71:14 — 'But as for me, I will hope continually' — into a declaration of what the psalmist intends to do regardless of outcome. Cycle 3 (71:17-24) opens with the biographical argument at full stretch (from youth to gray hair, 71:17-18), rises to a doxological climax (who is like You? 71:19), anticipates revival (71:20-21), and closes with full-body, instrumentally-accompanied jubilation (71:22-24). Each cycle descends deeper into the crisis and ascends higher into praise."
