          "title": "Righteousness as the psalm's spine — tsedaqah five times",
          "body": "The word tsedaqah (righteousness) appears five times in Psalm 71 (71:2, 15, 16, 19, 24), more than in almost any comparable psalm. This is not coincidental. The psalmist appeals to God's righteousness as the basis of deliverance (71:2), pledges to declare it as the content of testimony (71:15, 16, 24), and exalts it as cosmologically incomparable (71:19). In the Old Testament, tsedaqah is not merely a legal concept but a covenantal one — it is God acting in accordance with His promises to save His people. The psalmist is arguing that God's own character is committed to his rescue. This is why the enemies' taunt ('God has forsaken him') is not merely presumptuous but theologically incoherent: a God whose righteousness 'reaches to the heavens' (71:19) does not abandon the one in whom He has been trusted from birth."
