          "body": "What is most striking about Psalm 71 is that its resolution is entirely vocal and musical. The psalmist does not close with a report of rescue but with a pledge of proclamation. Mouth (71:8, 15), lips (71:23), tongue (71:24), harp (71:22), and lyre (71:22) are all explicitly named in the psalm's final movement. This is bodily theology: praise is not an internal disposition but a physical act performed with specific anatomical equipment and specific instruments. The full speech apparatus and the whole music ensemble are committed to telling God's righteousness. Spurgeon observes that when the soul has tasted God's faithfulness across a lifetime, the result is not quiet satisfaction but overflowing, uncontainable declaration. Psalm 71 is the theological charter for the testimony of the aged believer — one whose voice, precisely because it has been sustained through so many trials, carries peculiar authority to the next generation."
