        "title": "Refuge as permanent address — not emergency shelter",
        "range": "71:1-8",
        "excerpt": "In You, O LORD, I have taken refuge; let me never be ashamed. Be to me a rock of habitation to which I may continually come.",
        "body": "The psalm opens with a declaration before it opens with a petition: *In You, O LORD, I have taken refuge* (71:1). The verb *chasah* — to flee for shelter, to trust in as a stronghold — is the foundational act. The psalmist does not begin by describing his crisis; he begins by locating himself. He is already in the refuge. What follows in verses 1-4 are petitions that flow from this prior orientation: 'In Your righteousness deliver me' (71:2), 'Be to me a rock of habitation' (71:3), 'Rescue me from the hand of the wicked' (71:4). Each request is predicated on the reality already claimed.\n\nVerse 3 is theologically dense. The psalmist asks God to be 'a rock of habitation to which I may *continually* come' — the word *tamid* insisting that access to the refuge is not rationed. But then he immediately adds: 'You have given commandment to save me, for You are my rock and my fortress.' This is remarkable — the very thing he is asking for, God has already commanded. The petition and the prior divine decree are placed side by side. Calvin comments on comparable passages that the believer who prays in faith is not informing God of a need but aligning himself with what God has already purposed: the prayer is the instrument through which the decree takes effect.\n\nThe cluster of rock-imagery in verse 3 — *tsur* (cliff-rock), *sela* (crag), *matsudah* (stronghold or fortress) — draws on the Judean wilderness geography where flight to rocky terrain meant survival. David's years as a fugitive from Saul provided the experiential vocabulary. But the psalmist is doing more than invoking military metaphor. He is naming God as the permanent address — 'a rock of habitation,' a place to live, not merely to visit in danger. The God who is refuge is not a crisis intervention service but a dwelling-place.\n\nVerses 5-8 complete the first cycle by grounding the petition in biographical testimony. The confidence is not generated by the present crisis; it has been building since youth (71:5) and since birth (71:6). The extraordinary claim of verse 6 — 'You are He who took me from my mother's womb' — places God's sovereignty at the very origin of the psalmist's existence. Before his first conscious act of faith, God was already acting in his life. And the result of that sustained faithfulness is not relief but praise: 'My praise is continually of You' (71:6). The cycle closes with verse 8's summary: 'My mouth is filled with Your praise and with Your glory all day long.' The first eight verses are thus a complete unit — petition grounded in testimony, closed with vow.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chasah* (to take refuge, 71:1) is the root behind the common Psalter address 'You are my refuge.' *Tamid* (continually, 71:3, 6) — uninterrupted, perpetual. *Tsur* and *sela* are near-synonyms for rocky outcropping; *matsudah* is specifically a fortified stronghold — the three together pile up every dimension of the refuge metaphor."
