        "body": "Verse 9 names the psalm's defining fear with startling directness: 'Do not cast me off in the time of old age; do not forsake me when my strength fails.' Two verbs — *shalakh* (cast off, throw away) and *azav* (forsake, abandon) — pile up like the rock-imagery of verse 3, but now in the negative register. This is not a vague spiritual anxiety. The psalmist is aged, physically declining, and it is precisely this decline that has emboldened his enemies.\n\nVerses 10-11 give the specific content of the threat. The enemies have 'spoken against' the psalmist, 'consulted together,' and reached a theological verdict: 'God has forsaken him; pursue and seize him, for there is no one to deliver.' The enemy's logic is the psalm's central theological problem. They are reading the psalmist's weakness as divine abandonment. This is the ancient and recurring error — the equation of visible suffering with divine rejection. The book of Job exists to refute this equation in narrative form; Psalm 71 refutes it in lyric form. The psalmist does not argue against the inference directly; he simply refuses it: the God who sustained him from the womb (71:6) is the same God he is addressing now (71:12).\n\nThe urgency of verse 12 is notable: 'O God, do not be far from me; O my God, hasten to my help!' The doubling of address — 'O God... O my God' — and the command 'hasten' (*chish*, speed, hurry) indicate that the psalmist is not at leisure. The enemies are not a future threat; they are present and coordinated. And yet the petition is addressed to the same God of the prior eight verses — the permanent rock of habitation. The urgency of verse 12 is not panic; it is the urgency of one who knows exactly whom to call.\n\nVerse 13 closes the lament with an imprecatory petition: 'Let those who are adversaries of my soul be ashamed and consumed; let them be covered with reproach and dishonor.' This is not personal vindictiveness but covenantal theology. The enemies have made a theological claim — 'God has forsaken him' — and the psalmist prays that their shame will serve as God's public verdict against that claim. The adversaries' disgrace (71:13) and the psalmist's vindication are two sides of one divine act. Derek Kidner notes that imprecation in the Psalms is the flip-side of confidence in divine justice — it is the prayer of those who have no other court of appeal.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Azav* (forsake, abandon, 71:9, 11, 18) — the same word used in Psalm 22:1 ('My God, my God, why have You forsaken me?') and Deuteronomy 31:6 ('He will not fail you or forsake you'). *Satan* in 71:13 (translated 'adversaries') is the common noun for accuser, not the proper name of the supernatural figure — though the legal connotation of accusation is present and relevant."
