        "excerpt": "But as for me, I will hope continually, and will praise You yet more and more.",
        "body": "Verse 14 is the psalm's great rhetorical hinge. Against the enemies' organized conspiracy of verses 10-11, the psalmist sets a single counter-resolve: 'But as for me, I will hope continually, and will praise You yet more and more.' The adversative 'but' (*wa'ani*, literally 'and I') functions as the pivot on which the entire psalm turns. What the enemies intend is irrelevant to what the psalmist intends. Their strategy is attack and capture; his strategy is hope and praise.\n\nThe word *yachal* (hope, wait with confident expectation, 71:14) is paired with *tamid* (continually) — the same adverb used for the rock of habitation (71:3) and for the praise (71:6). The psalmist's hope is not episodic, generated by favorable circumstances; it is constitutional, the permanent orientation of a life given to God. Keller notes that biblical hope is not optimism (a calculation of probability) but confidence in a specific promise from a specific Person. The psalmist hopes continually because the object of his hope — the God of 71:3-7 — is perpetually reliable.\n\nVerses 15-16 specify what the hope produces: testimony. 'My mouth shall tell of Your righteousness and of Your salvation all day long; for I do not know the sum of them' (71:15). The psalmist cannot count God's righteous acts — the testimony is inexhaustible. This is not hyperbole; it is the confession of a man who has lived long enough to accumulate more evidences than he can organize. He will 'come with the mighty deeds of the Lord GOD' (71:16), approaching God's presence loaded with the weight of what God has done. And then the remarkable phrase: 'I will make mention of Your righteousness, Yours alone' (*tsedaqah usvadcha levadecha* — 'of Your righteousness, Yours only'). The exclusivity is deliberate. In a world of competing claims about what saves and what sustains, the psalmist will mention only one source.\n\nThe rhetorical movement of this section — from crisis (71:9-13) through adversative resolve (71:14) to inexhaustible testimony (71:15-16) — embodies what Hendricks calls the 'interpretive principle of contrast': the most revealing moment in any text is where the author plants a 'but.' Here the 'but' is the hinge of the psalm's entire argument. The enemies expected shame; the psalmist produces praise. The enemies predicted silence; the psalmist promises speech. This counter-resolve is not manufactured courage; it is the natural overflow of a lifetime of experienced faithfulness (71:5-8).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Wa'ani* ('but as for me,' 71:14) — emphatic first person, setting the psalmist's stance against what has preceded. *Yachal* (hope, 71:14) — to wait with expectation, to anticipate; the root of *tiqvah* (the noun for hope, 71:5). *Tsedaqah levadecha* (Your righteousness, Yours alone, 71:16) — *bad* (alone, only) is emphatic exclusivity."
