        "title": "Old age as the platform for generational proclamation",
        "range": "71:17-19",
        "excerpt": "O God, You have taught me from my youth, and I still declare Your wondrous deeds. And even when I am old and gray, O God, do not forsake me, until I declare Your strength to this generation.",
        "body": "The third cycle opens with the psalm's most explicit biographical sweep. Verse 17 states the lifelong curriculum: 'O God, You have taught me from my youth, and I still declare Your wondrous deeds.' The verb *lamad* (taught, instructed) is the root of the word *talmid* (disciple). The psalmist has been God's student from the beginning, and the content of the curriculum has been God's *pala* — His wondrous deeds, works too extraordinary for ordinary explanation. The implication is that the psalmist's testimony is not self-generated insight but received instruction declared outward.\n\nVerse 18 adds the urgency: 'And even when I am old and gray, O God, do not forsake me, until I declare Your strength to this generation, Your power to all who are to come.' The prayer against forsaking (the third use of *azav* in the psalm) now has an explicit purpose clause: 'until I declare.' The psalmist is not asking for longevity for its own sake — comfort, dignity, ease in old age. He is asking for enough time and enough health to complete the transmission of what he has received. This is the psalm's most missiological verse: old age, in the biblical frame, is not the conclusion of usefulness but the moment when accumulated testimony becomes most valuable to the next generation.\n\nVerse 19 rises to the psalm's highest doxological register: 'For Your righteousness, O God, reaches to the heavens; You who have done great things; O God, who is like You?' The spatial metaphor — righteousness reaching to *marom* (the heights, the heavens) — is the psalm's most expansive claim. No human situation, however deep, falls outside the reach of a righteousness that extends to the heavens. The rhetorical question 'Who is like You?' (*mi khamokha*) echoes the Song of Moses (Exodus 15:11) and is the standard Old Testament formula for divine incomparability. The one who has no comparator is the one being asked not to forsake an old man. The disproportion between the cosmic scope of verse 19 and the vulnerability of the psalmist is itself the argument: the God who is cosmically incomparable will not fail the particular old man who has trusted Him from birth.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pala* (wondrous deeds, 71:17) — acts that exceed ordinary causation, that demand a divine explanation. *Zeroa* (strength/arm, 71:18) and *gevurah* (might, 71:18) — the arm of God is the standard Old Testament idiom for God's saving power deployed in history (cf. Exodus 6:6; Deuteronomy 4:34). *Mi kamokha* (who is like You?, 71:19) — the incomparability formula, common in Second Isaiah as well as Exodus."
