        "title": "Revival from the depths — and the soul's jubilant answer",
        "range": "71:20-24",
        "excerpt": "You who have shown me many troubles and distresses will revive me again, and will bring me up again from the depths of the earth. My lips will shout for joy when I sing praises to You; and my soul, which You have redeemed.",
        "body": "Verses 20-21 constitute one of the psalm's most daring theological moves. The psalmist does not merely pray for rescue from present trouble — he names God as the agent of the prior troubles: 'You who have shown me many troubles and distresses' (*ra'itani*). This is the same God he has been addressing in prayer. The troubles were not accidental, not the result of divine inattention, but something 'shown' — deliberately permitted or ordained — by the God who is his refuge. This is not bitterness; it is a mature theological acknowledgment that the same sovereignty that permits suffering is the sovereignty that reverses it: 'Will revive me again, and will bring me up again from the depths of the earth' (71:20). The word *tehom* (depths) echoes the primordial deep of Genesis 1:2 and the abyss of Jonah 2:6 — it is the language of near-death and death itself. God's capacity to bring up from there is the ultimate expression of His power.\n\nVerse 21 adds the note of honor: 'May You increase my greatness and turn to comfort me.' The word *gedulah* (greatness, honor) is unexpected after the vocabulary of vulnerability in verses 9-18. But it belongs to the covenantal reversal pattern of the Psalter: the one who is shamed by enemies will be honored by God; the one the world considered forsaken will be comforted. This is the same arc as Psalm 22 — from 'My God, why have You forsaken me' (22:1) to 'He has not despised or disdained the suffering of the afflicted one' (22:24). And it anticipates what Paul will name as the pattern of resurrection hope: 'I consider that the sufferings of this present time are not worth comparing with the glory that is to be revealed' (Romans 8:18).\n\nThe closing verses (71:22-24) are the psalm's fullest orchestration of praise. Harp (*keli* — instrument), lyre (*kinnor*), lips, soul, and tongue are all enrolled in the final declaration. The instruments are addressed to God's *emet* (truth/faithfulness) and the person is addressed to God's holiness: 'O Holy One of Israel' (71:22) — a title used extensively by Isaiah (Isaiah 1:4; 12:6; 41:14) and here by the psalmist in a unique convergence. The soul that was watched for by enemies (71:10) has been redeemed (*padah*, 71:23 — ransomed, bought out). The tongue that enemies hoped would fall silent will 'utter Your righteousness all day long' (71:24). And the enemies themselves 'are ashamed, for they are humiliated who seek my hurt' (71:24) — completing the reversal the psalmist prayed for in 71:13.\n\nThe psalm ends not with a report of rescue but with a posture of praise. We do not know whether the enemies were defeated or the psalmist delivered. What we know is that his mouth is full, his lips are shouting, his soul has been named redeemed, and his tongue has been committed to declaration. The resolution is rhetorical and theological before it is circumstantial. This is the psalm's final pastoral lesson: the posture of praise is not the reward for answered prayer — it is the environment in which faith waits.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chayah* (revive, 71:20) — to restore to life, to bring back from the verge of death; the root behind the Ezekiel 37 valley of dry bones ('I will cause breath to enter you, and you will come to life,' *chayah*). *Padah* (redeemed, 71:23) — to redeem by payment, ransom; specifically the act of a kinsman-redeemer paying a price to recover what was forfeited. *Qadosh Yisrael* (Holy One of Israel, 71:22) — Isaiah's characteristic title for God, here placed on the psalmist's lips as his instrument of praise."
